Subject:    <a href="?t=95837889000035&r=1&w=2">Gratuitous use of the domain system</a>
From:       <a href="?a=95837784800006&r=1&w=2">&lt;mar () ATHENA ! MIT ! EDU&gt;</a>
Date:       <a href="?l=namedroppers&r=1&w=2&b=198710">1987-10-21 11:31:08</a></font>
[Download RAW <a href="?l=namedroppers&m=95837781926956&q=mbox">message</a> or <a href="?l=namedroppers&m=95837781926956&q=raw">body</a>]</b>

But you can store other things with the domain naming system.  Here at
Project Athena we use a system we call hesiod, which is just bind with
slightly better support for unspecified record types.  Then we have
databases of class HS instead of IN, which have all of the hesiod
data.  In this we store mappings from hostnames to fileservers and
default printers, user names to password file entries and post
offices, and lots of other configuration information.

 When I log in to a public workstation, it resolves
"mar.passwd.ns.athena.mit.edu", which returns
"mar:*:17822:101:Mark A. Rosenstein,,E40-331M,1530,:/mit/mar:/bin/csh"
and that gets temporarily put in /etc/passwd.  While we had to make
some small changes in the nameserver to support this, we are using the
standard protocol.
					-Mark

